  "lesson_en": "A righteous man loyal to the end; though betrayed, God will remember",
  "summary_en": "Uriah the Hittite, one of David's mighty men, husband of Bathsheba. After David sinned he summoned Uriah home to cover his crime, but Uriah, because the ark and his comrades were on the battlefield, would not go home to enjoy himself, and was finally killed at the front by David's design via the Ammonites' sword.",
  "witness_en": "Uriah was a Gentile, yet more loyal to Israel's God and people than Israel's king. He said: 'The ark and Israel and Judah dwell in tents... shall I then go to my house to eat and drink and lie with my wife?' Even being made drunk by the king could not shake this loyalty. He carried the letter containing his own death sentence to the battlefield, faithful to the end without suspicion. This innocent, loyal man was betrayed to death by those in power, and his blood and his name (Matt 1:6, 'the wife of Uriah') remain forever in Scripture, witnessing that God does not forget the wronged righteous.",
  "prayer_en": "Lord Jesus, You are the wholly innocent One betrayed and condemned to death by those in power; Uriah's wrong is a shadow of You, and finds its answer in Your resurrection. Give me a spirit faithful unto death, learning from You not to retaliate when wronged, but to entrust all to the just Father. Amen.",
